{
  "query": "For arable fields in the Mediterranean, how does a no-tillage system compare with a reduced tillage system for improving soil health?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on Mediterranean studies, both no-tillage and reduced tillage systems improve soil health compared to conventional tillage, with some differences between them. No-tillage consistently shows benefits for soil organic matter, with studies from Spain finding more organic matter in no-tillage systems compared to reduced tillage (action 1370). A meta-analysis of Mediterranean countries found more organic matter in no-tillage soils compared to tilled soils (action 1369), and another meta-analysis found more organic matter in reduced tillage compared to conventional tillage (action 1371).\n\nFor soil nutrients, results are mixed. No-tillage systems show varied effects on nitrogen compared to reduced tillage - some studies found more nitrogen (action 1370), while others found less or similar amounts (actions 1369, 1370). Both systems generally increase phosphorus levels compared to conventional tillage, with no-tillage sometimes showing more phosphorus than reduced tillage (action 1370).\n\nRegarding soil organisms, both systems support microbial biomass. No-tillage and reduced tillage show similar microbial biomass levels in most cases, though some studies found more microbial biomass in no-tillage systems (actions 1369, 1370). Both systems support earthworm populations better than conventional tillage, with studies finding more earthworms in no-tillage fields (action 1369).\n\nFor soil structure and erosion control, both systems improve soil aggregation and stability compared to conventional tillage. No-tillage sometimes shows better water-stability and formation of larger aggregates compared to reduced tillage, though results vary (action 1370). Studies from Spain found that both no-tillage and reduced tillage create more stable soils than conventional tillage (actions 1369, 1371).\n\nIn terms of greenhouse gases, both systems show variable effects on carbon dioxide emissions, with no clear consistent difference between no-tillage and reduced tillage systems (actions 1369, 1370, 1371).",
